name: Edward Winslow II
death_place: At Sea Between Hispaniola and Jamaica, West Indies. On the passage to attack Jamaica, he became ill of fever and died. His remains were buried at sea with the honors of war and a 42-gun salute.
death_city: At Sea Between Hispaniola and Jamaica, West Indies. On the passage to attack Jamaica, he became ill of fever and died. His remains were buried at sea with the honors of war and a 42-gun salute.
notes:
Mayflower Passenger\Signer of Mayflower Compact, 3rd, 6th and 10th Governor of Plymouth Colony.

Edward Winslow (1595-1655) was a key leader of the Plymouth Colony, a passenger on the Mayflower, and served as governor of the colony three times. He was a diplomat with the Wampanoag people, an author of important colonial texts like Mourt's Relation, and was the only Mayflower passenger with a confirmed contemporary portrait. He died in 1655 from a fever while on a government expedition in the West Indies and was buried at sea. 

Edward Winslow is well known as a passenger on the Mayflower and one of the early leaders of the Plymouth Colony. He served three times as governor of the colony and was an assistant governor on numerous occasions. He was fervent defender of the colonies in New England and made several trips back to England to defend the colonies from opponents and to obtain much needed support. He also wrote a number of publications in defense of the colonies which greatly help our understanding of the settlement of the new world.
He was married twice, first to Elizabeth Barker and then to Susanna Jackson. His second marriage was the first in the newly established colony. He had five known children by his second wife, but only one son and one daughter survived to leave descendants.
In 1655, he was the chief of the three English commissioners whom Cromwell sent on his expedition against the West Indies to advise with its leaders Admiral Venables and Admiral William Penn, but died near Jamaica (Anderson says near Hispaniola) on the 8th of May 1655, aged 59y, 6m, 18d, and was buried at sea.
Birth
Baptized: 20 October 1595 at the parish of St. Peter's in Droitwich, Worcestershire, England.[1][2][3]
He was the son of Edward Winslow and Magdalen Oliver.

name: John "the Fortune" Winslow
notes:
John "the Fortune" Winslow (1597–1674) was an early colonial figure in New England who arrived on the ship Fortune in 1621, a ship nicknamed for his financially successful future. He was the brother of Mayflower passengers Edward and Gilbert Winslow. After arriving in Plymouth, he later moved to Boston where he became a successful merchant and shipowner. Winslow married Mary Chilton, a daughter of Mayflower passenger James Chilton. 
Arrival: Came to Plymouth Colony in 1621 on the ship Fortune.
Family: His brother, Edward Winslow, was a passenger on the Mayflower and a leader in the Plymouth Colony. He married Mary Chilton in 1624.
Career: Became a successful merchant and shipowner in Boston after moving there around 1655.
Later Life: He and his wife transferred their church membership to Boston in 1671 and are buried in the King's Chapel Burying Ground.
Death: Died in Boston in 1674.

name: John Wesley Shelburne
notes:
Died in Eagle, Colorado in 1858.
n 1858, the town of Eagle, Colorado did not exist; the first gold rush discoveries were near Cherry Creek, which would eventually lead to Denver. The area that is now Eagle was part of the vast wilderness named after the Eagle River. At the time, Colorado was a territory, not a state. 
Colorado Gold Rush: In 1858, gold was discovered along Ralston Creek and the South Platte River, kicking off the Colorado Gold Rush. This brought thousands of prospectors to the area, leading to the establishment of settlements like Auraria and Denver.
No Eagle settlement: The town of Eagle wasn't incorporated until 1905, and its post office didn't open until 1891. The county, Eagle County, was created in 1883 and named for the Eagle River, which flows through the region.
A territorial government: In 1858, Colorado was not yet a state; it was part of the Kansas Territory. It would not be admitted to the Union as a state until 1876.
